    "created_at": "2025-12-01T14:35:56.209882+00:00",
    "updated_at": "2025-12-09T22:54:02.1+00:00",
    "coach_notes": ":\nSnatch workout - ZT - https://youtu.be/rV1OsGZS_R0?si=kmpNc-SUd4sBevGW\n\nCatalyst Exercise Library - https://www.catalystathletics.com/exercises/\n\nEarly Arm Bend in the Snatch & Clean - Catalyst\n\nWomens 75kg 2018 European Weightlifting Championship - Lydia Valentin\nMens 94kg 2018 European Weightlifting Championship\n\nCatalyst Warm-Up - https://youtu.be/XF5LLh7kmfk\nCatalyst Dynamic Warm-Up - https://youtu.be/XhHc7FbSUiY\n\nBarbell Snatch Technique Primers:\nDip Muscle Snatch - Catalyst - https://www.catalystathletics.com/exercise/464/Dip-Muscle-Snatch/\nMuscle Snatch from Power Position - Monroe Miller - https://www.facebook.com/reel/543227008885980\n\nMuscle Snatch from Power Position - https://www.catalystathletics.com/exercise/466/Muscle-Snatch-From-Power-Position/\n\nExecution:\nStart standing tall with the bar hanging at arms’ length in your snatch grip. \nEnsure even whole foot balance and brace your trunk. \nBend at the knees only with a vertical trunk just as you would for a jerk, actively pushing the bar against your hips, and stop.\nAfter a 1-2 second pause, drive up with the legs and complete a muscle snatch.\nFocus on keeping the bar as close as possible, finishing with strong vertical leg drive, and punching vertically into the overhead position at the end of the turnover.\nIt can be helpful to think of the movement as a snatch high-pull with an added turnover of the bar afterward. This will reinforce the idea of driving vertically and lifting the elbows high and out before the turnover.\nThe only difference between a dip muscle snatch and a muscle snatch from power position is that there is a pause in the bottom of the dip in the muscle snatch from power position. \n\nPurpose\nThe muscle snatch is helpful to learn, reinforce and strengthen the proper upper body mechanics of the turnover (third pull) of the snatch. The power position variation helps focus on vertical leg drive and better bar-body interaction to improve bar proximity. The abbreviated motion can also be used to reduce the contribution of the legs and place more emphasis on upper body strength. From power position relative to dip will allow more focus on proper position, balance and leg drive.\n\nRep scheme:\n6 x Muscle Snatch from Power Position with PVC Pipe on coach's cue\n6 x Muscle Snatch from Power position with Empty Bar on coach's cue\n6 x Dip Muscle Snatch with Empty Bar on coach's cue\nAdd weight for sets of 3-4\n\nHang Power Snatch Practice (6 mins)\n1 minute Snatch Tutorial\nWork up to WOD weight for Hang Power Snatch\nsets of 2 x HPS + 1 OHS\nmins 41-44\n\nWOD 12 min AMRAP\n2 x Chest Touch Bear Crawl over the Bar (1 x fwds, 1 x bwds. Start in Bear Crawl position, touch chest to ground, BC over the bar, touch chest to ground, reverse BC over the bar, touch chest to ground)\n4 x Hang Power Snatch\n2 x Barbell Overhead Squats",
